Since I said I'd share some of the survey responses I got from Where Kitsune Wait, here are some interesting responses to the question about whether people want more art.
>Saki and Egil in the fight. Something out of a Fantasy Poster or Cover art. Or have Rin in there somewhere. Think Trials of Mana posters.
>Meiko :^>
>Miki
>Some of the ideas that you decided not to put in the story, some sort of "what if" scenario.
>Maybe something depicting Rin's personal struggle between professionalism and protection of her family, against her desire for Egil? Of maybe a less metaphorical fight in regards to the Kappa scene, or the encounter with Lost Sister (dammit, forgot her name). The story hasn't seen anything lewd, but maybe in that vane an image of Egil bathing with the implication of the number of Kitsune watching him?

Honorary mentions for the most ambitious suggestions:
>would like to see more of the kitsune home and its residents... i'd be interested to see if an artist can do any justice to your descriptions of such a comfortable sounding place.
>Egil and Saki by the campfire, or a group pic with Rin, Saki, Shizuka, Miki, and Egil.
>Kitsune family photo

Creating an anthro would be blending two sets of DNA (human and animal) into a single organism. Or taking an animal and tweaking it so much it becomes intelligent as a human and able to walk upright. People underestimate just how difficult that would be. CRISPR was the one thing that made me think it might be happening, but we are still just barely scratching the surface with genetics. The day they say "We've engineered a strawberry that can resist pests and can grow as big as a pumpkin" then I will consider that we will one day engineer something that resemble people. To create a stable organism that isn't a horrifying mess that dies within the first 5 minutes of being born. That would require level 50 genetic engineering. At the moment we're at a decent level 6. Curing cancer and ending world hunger would be far easier.

I do agree it could happen if we can extend human lifespans. If we cure aging somehow and all live to be 250 years old, then the sky is the limit. But to have it happen within the next 50 years... I highly doubt it.

We don't have enough poetry.
It's deliberately vague with one exception, so fill in the blanks as you wish.

One blue flower on the nightstand,
Same as the orphan this morning
Left amongst concrete and traffic,
Not one stopped to observe but me.

Not wilted but without a place
Of her own, waiting quietly
While commuters were racing past
And joggers paced with senses blind.

The night is not as the morning
With dark lighting eyes unseeing
But mine ready to close in sleep
As I placed myself on the bed.

Along that way early this morn
There were flowers of red and white,
Yellow and green, orangey golds,
Every color except for blue.

On the return, yes, I stopped
At that flower, urban alone
And took it willingly from there
Knowing fully what I'd just done.

Flowers die, removed from the earth
But that is the way of all things
And never forgetting the ones
Of charitable jealousy.

To desire the unique is joy
So I chose not what shared my form.
Into the blue I’d drown myself
For many nights before and since.

I never asked where she was from,
She never cared of our diff’rence.
Each breath a lifetime that we shared
Beholden to none except us.

Each night we shared our love again,
For I knew of those that exclaimed
The virtue of scale or feather,
Of feline or canine as mate.

I‘d never considered the act
To be alike her smile beaming,
Or different hands clasped in public.
We shared that lesson every day.

Somewhere my distant friends had found
The same fate as me; some floating
Kisses on the top of a beak,
Some coiled after sharing their warmth.

Our bodies entwined, now apart,
The only detail I cared of
Was eyes of blue, though mine briefly
Before sleep, human and other.
